  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3050640889" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3050640889" />
    <a title="Julie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5211606-julie"><img alt="Julie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1505571524p2/5211606.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3050640889?book_show_action=true">Dec 20, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Julie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Julie" href="/user/show/5211606-julie">Julie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/33597976-the-snow-child">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5211606-julie?shelf=reading-road-trip-2020">reading-road-trip-2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5211606-julie?shelf=the-winter-of-our-discontent">the-winter-of-our-discontent</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5211606-julie?shelf=baked-alaska">baked-alaska</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3050640889" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15141672185617266932"><b>Reading Road Trip 2020</b><br/><br/>Current location: <b>Alaska</b><br/><br/><b>Alaska gave up nothing easily. It was lean and wild and indifferent to a man&apos;s struggle. . . </b><br/><br/>I don&apos;t know how old Eowyn Ivey was when she started this debut novel, <i>The Snow Child</i>, but I&apos;m going to guess she was relatively young. It&apos;s filled with many rookie mistakes I made in my own first novel: a strong primary protagonist surrounded by several lesser formed characters, the action of the story reduced to one primary setting, and a few loose plot poi</span>
  <span id="freeText15141672185617266932" style="display:none"><b>Reading Road Trip 2020</b><br /><br />Current location: <b>Alaska</b><br /><br /><b>Alaska gave up nothing easily. It was lean and wild and indifferent to a man's struggle. . . </b><br /><br />I don't know how old Eowyn Ivey was when she started this debut novel, <i>The Snow Child</i>, but I'm going to guess she was relatively young. It's filled with many rookie mistakes I made in my own first novel: a strong primary protagonist surrounded by several lesser formed characters, the action of the story reduced to one primary setting, and a few loose plot points that require suspension of disbelief from the reader.<br /><br />In many ways, this debut work to me feels like an early draft of what would later become <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1796748283?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1" rel="nofollow noopener">The Bright Edge of the World</a>. The storylines are very similar: a childless couple dealing with the unforgiving and beautiful environs of Alaska, letter writing as an important vehicle for plot, and an encounter with a fledgling child of mystical origins. <br /><br />I'm not sure why Ms. Ivey has written about the same thing, twice. I'm also not sure why she depicted this couple, Jack and Mabel, as so old. . . so very, very old (in their late 40s!), and introduced them to us as “estranged” or at the very least, drifting apart to the point of not speaking almost once in an entire day, to having them engage in almost unbelievable amounts of sexual activity.<br /><br />I mean. . . I'm glad <i>someone</i>'s having sex during this pandemic, but the scene where the couple, after killing, boiling and plucking the feathers off of twelve of their chickens, find themselves engaging in foreplay was really almost too much for me. As a reader, I was turning green at the descriptions of what the room smelled like (singed bird skin and dirty feathers), so imagine my surprise when Jack wants to <i>get it on</i>. As they hit the floor in a frenzy of feathers and lust, I think I threw up a little in my mouth in surprise.<br /><br />Honestly, their little corner of Alaska was so cold, dirty and smelly (and lacking in dental floss), I think I would have finally accepted celibacy as my fate, but these two could go from no conversation to screwing the chicken feathers right off of each other in five minutes flat. Apparently moose steaks are a natural aphrodisiac.<br /><br />And the kid. . . the little snow child. This kid gave me the CREEPS. Nothing about her made any sense (most especially the ending). I kept thinking of her as Stephen King's famous little fire starter: a devil child. She never worked for me, as a character, and I kept hoping they'd padlock the door or move, every time she left their cabin. <br /><br />I also could have lived without the woefully unformed Mabel, who could only say: “Oh,” over and over again, but who sketched like John James Audubon (again, just like the protagonist in THE BRIGHT EDGE OF THE WORLD).<br /><br />Okay, so I'm bitching and moaning, and you're getting uptight because you loved this book and that creepy little kid, but you shouldn't be, because there's this other less bitchy part of me that wants to tell you what's so great about Eowyn Ivey's writing: she's a STORYTELLER, and many, many writers are not. She's a storyteller, and that makes you turn the pages of her stories as though you need to fan a fire with them. She delights me, terribly, in her ability to prove to me that the human imagination hasn't died.<br /><br />She's also a NATURALIST, and she made the state of Alaska a <i>character</i>. Quite brilliantly, too. She not only shows us how Alaska “draws kooks like flies;” she shows us her greatest secrets, how beautiful and dangerous she can be. <br /><br />The snow child, Faina, is that dangerous beauty, personified, and I can't help but think that the husband, Jack, represents the writer, Jack London, who brought Alaska to most of us for the very first time.<br /><br />Ms. Ivey is also a PSYCHOLOGIST. I've noticed that in both of her novels, to manages to have better insights than some therapists, into what divides men and woman apart and what brings them back together.<br /><br />(Chicken feathers. Duh).<br /><br />I preferred TO THE BRIGHT EDGE OF THE WORLD, because, well, it's basically <i>this</i> story, done better. This is a beauty of a debut, though, with a stunning cover to boot. The state of Alaska just couldn't ask for a better way to increase tourism.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15141672185617266932" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

